\b\fs28 I. Additional Multiplayer Information\par
\b0\fs20\par
\pard\b\fs24 Network Settings\par
\b0\fs20\par
To insure the highest level of multiplayer game quality, you should specify your connection type in Network Settings. Not only does this setting determine the maximum number of players you can host on a game, but it also determines the amount of data that you will receive from other servers when you are connecting to a multiplayer game as a player. \par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar To specify your network settings:\par
\pard\fi-360\li490\ri360\sb100\sa1\sl288\slmult1\tx720 1.\tab On the Halo main screen, click \b Settings\b0 .\par
\pard\fi-360\li490\ri360\sb100\sa1\sl288\slmult1 2.\tab Click \b Network Setup\b0 . \par
3.\tab Select the appropriate connection type.\par
4.\tab Click \b OK\b0 .\par
\pard\par
\b\fs24 Direct IP Connection\par
\b0\f1\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\f0\fs20 You can join an Internet multiplayer game using a specific IP address for the host server. The host address can be a computer name or numerical IP address.\par
\par
To join a game using Direct IP:\par
\pard\fi-360\li490\ri360\sb100\sa1\sl288\slmult1\tx720 1.\tab On the Halo main screen, click \b Multiplayer\b0 .\par
\pard\fi-360\li490\ri360\sb100\sa1\sl288\slmult1 2.\tab Click \b Direct IP\b0  under Join. \par
3.\tab Enter the IP address for the host server.\par
4.\tab Enter a password (if required).\par
5.\tab Click \b Join\b0  to join the game. \par
\pard\ri360\sb100\sa1\sl288\slmult1 Notes: \par
\pard\fi-360\li720\ri360\sb100\sa1\sl288\slmult1\tx720\f3\'b7\tab\f0 Halo remembers the last host address you typed in.\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\ri360\sb100\sa1\tx720\f3\'b7\tab\f0 If there is no game at the specified IP address, then a \ldblquote Connection Failed\rdblquote  dialog box is displayed. When you click OK, you are returned to the Multiplayer screen. Try entering the IP address again, using the steps above. If that doesn\rquote t work, you should contact the person hosting the game to verify the IP address for the host server.\par
\pard\b\fs24\par
Checking for Updates\par
\b0\fs20\par
Each time you join or create an Internet multiplayer game, Halo automatically checks for the latest update on the Internet. A dialog box is displayed indicating that Halo is \ldblquote checking for updates.\rdblquote  If there is an update available, your current game is shut down, the update is downloaded and installed, and the game is restarted. \par
\par
If you choose to cancel out of your update, then you are returned to the Multiplayer screen. The next time you attempt to join or create an Internet multiplayer game, the process starts all over again. If there is a Halo update available, you must allow the update to download and install if you wish to continue. If you wish to manually update your game, please visit http://www.microsoft.com/games/halo/default.asp.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\b\fs28\par
J. Multiplayer Troubleshooting\par
\cf2\b0\fs20\par
This section describes the known multiplayer issues and workarounds.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\tx360\tx720\cf0\par
\b Ports Used by the Game\par
\pard\b0 Halo connects to the Internet on the following ports by default:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sb100\sa10\tx720\f5\'a7\tab\f0 2302 (UDP)\emdash Game host listens on this port\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sb100\sa10\f5\'a7\tab\f0 2303 (UDP)\emdash Game client connects to host through this port\par
\pard\sb100 Halo will run from behind most routers and Network Address Translation (NAT) devices. If you have difficulty connecting from behind a router, you should consult your router documentation to ensure that the ports listed above are not blocked for your PC.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\tx360\tx720\par
\pard Halo checks for updates via HTTP in the same way a Web browser would. If you use Windows XP SP-1, Halo can use an auto-detectable proxy server on your network, but does not currently support manually-set proxies. If your network requires you to manually set your proxy server, please visit www.microsoft.com/games/halo to check for updates, which you can download manually. \par
\par
To check your proxy settings:\par
\pard\fi-576\li706\ri360\sb100\sa1\tx720 1.\tab Launch Internet Explorer\par
\pard\fi-576\li706\ri360\sb100\sa1 2.\tab From the \b Tools\b0  menu, click \b Internet Options\b0 .\par
3.\tab Click \b Connections\b0 .\par
4.\tab If you connect to the Internet manually, double-click on the appropriate connection in the list at the top. If you connect via a Local Area Network (LAN), click \b LAN Settings\b0 .\par
5.\tab Under \b Proxy server\b0 , verify that the settings are correct for proxy server that you or your network administrator has set up.\par
\pard\li130\ri360\par
\pard If you are connected to the Internet and can reach http://www.microsoft.com, for example, your proxy settings are correct.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\tx360\tx720\par
\b In non-team games (such as Slayer), all vehicles are spawning in front of the Red Base:\b0  You must select two of each type of vehicle to ensure that one vehicle gets placed in both the Red Base and Blue Base. In non-team games, the default base is Red when vehicles are assigned. If there is only one type of vehicle spawned, then only the Red Base will be populated with vehicles.\par
\par
\b Damage-confirmation beep:\b0  You may want turn off the damage-confirmation beep in multiplayer games. To do this, you must use the Debug Console. To activate the Debug Console, run Halo with the \b -console\b0  command prompt (see the Command Prompts section above), press \b ~\b0  in the game to enable the Debug Console, and then type \b should_play_multiplayer_hit_sound 0\b0 .\par
\b\par
\pard Unable to join a Direct IP multiplayer game hosted behind a NAT device or router, or on an Internet Connection Sharing (ICS) Server in Windows 98 Second Edition, Windows Me, and Windows 2000: \b0 You need to join multiplayer games that are hosted behind a router or on an ICS server via the Gamespy Lobby.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\tx360\tx720\par
\b Unable to join a multiplayer game with an Internet Connection Sharing (ICS) Client on Windows 2000 or Windows XP:\b0  You may have difficulty joining a multiplayer game if a person using a Windows 2000 or Windows XP ICS client has joined and exited that game before you attempt to join it.\par
\b\par
Unable to browse for games on a local area network (LAN) on a machine with two network adaptors in Windows XP: \b0 You may not be able to browse for multiplayer games on a LAN if the two network connections are not configured correctly. The Internet must be configured on the first network connection, and the LAN needs to be configured on the second internet connection. For more information on configuring a network connection, click \b Start\b0 , and then click \b Help and Support\b0 . \par
\par
\b Microsoft Base Station MN500:\b0  Halo does not offer automatic NAT negotiation of UPnP devices such as the MN500. If you have difficulties connecting to games or hosting a server behind this device, you should manually set it to forward the required ports\emdash 2302 and 2303 (UDP) by default\emdash to the IP address of the game computer behind the router.\par
